# Lightweight Architecture

## Trigger Handler Pattern

One trigger per object, handler extends `TriggerHandler` base class. Logic lives directly in handlers.

```apex
trigger AccountTrigger on Account (before insert, before update, after insert, after update) {
    new AccountTriggerHandler().run();
}

public class AccountTriggerHandler extends TriggerHandler {
    protected override void beforeInsert() {
        // Logic directly in handler
    }
}
```

## Guidelines

- No service layer required - logic in handlers or utility classes
- No domain layer - validation in trigger handlers
- No selector layer - SOQL in handlers or query helpers
- Keep it flat - avoid unnecessary abstraction
- Extract to utility class only when handler exceeds ~200 lines
- Don't create fflib_* classes or UnitOfWork patterns

## Async
- Async classes are standalone — query and DML directly, no service layer
- Enqueue from trigger handlers

## Configuration
- Query CMDTs directly with `getAll()`, cache in static variables
- Use `System.Label.My_Label` for user-facing text
- Use `My_Settings__c.getInstance()` for per-user overrides
- Keep it simple — a static utility at most, no selector pattern for config

## LWC
- Controllers are simple `@AuraEnabled` Apex classes — no service layer delegation
- Business logic can live directly in the controller for small components
- Use `WITH SECURITY_ENFORCED` in controller SOQL
- Reference `references/lwc-patterns.md` for full patterns
